{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774458176,"nonce":"tWwGTebKyayrcOJ2IDXL2OxhvZI=","title":"Part 2 analysis: PCA and tangling during reaching","message":"Umbrella: 0af472c (Part 2)\n\n**Motivation:** Tangling measures how \"tangled\" the neural trajectories are in state space -- high tangling means similar states lead to very different derivatives, indicating fragile dynamics. Does SISU reduce tangling by separating neural trajectories for different perturbation conditions?\n\n**Approach:** Perform PCA on hidden states (aggregated over pert amp and SISU for a shared basis), then compute tangling in PC space. The tangling metric is RMS over time (excluding t=0). Compare tangling distributions across SISU levels and perturbation amplitudes via violin plots.\n\n**Status:** Module exists at `src/rlrmp/modules/analysis/part2/tangling.py`. Implements `StatesPCA` dependency aggregated over labels, `Tangling` with `CallWithDeps` to use PCA transform, and violin plots. RMS tangling aggregation is a post-hoc transform.\n\n**References:** Russo et al. (2018) for tangling metric; Kaufman et al. (2014) for neural population dynamics during reaching.","files":null}]}